WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.090 --> 00:00:09.730
LAURA: Hi, everyone and welcome.

00:00:09.730 --> 00:00:13.330
And thank you so much
for joining us today.

00:00:13.330 --> 00:00:14.280
My name is Laura.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:16.650
I work on accessibility
here at Google.

00:00:16.650 --> 00:00:18.550
It's great to be here today.

00:00:18.550 --> 00:00:22.290
And accessibility is something
that's really, really critical

00:00:22.290 --> 00:00:24.961
and core to our
mission here at Google.

00:00:24.961 --> 00:00:26.460
To organize the
world's information,

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:29.650
make it universally
accessible and useful.

00:00:29.650 --> 00:00:33.870
And 15% of the global population
has some form of disability.

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:36.420
And we need to be thinking
about how people are actually

00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:39.142
interacting with our interfaces
and with our devices.

00:00:39.142 --> 00:00:41.100
Kind of stripping away
those assumptions of how

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:42.724
we might think that
they're interacting

00:00:42.724 --> 00:00:46.129
and really building
inclusive products.

00:00:46.129 --> 00:00:48.420
When we are thinking about
the principles of accessible

00:00:48.420 --> 00:00:51.900
design, it's often helpful to
kind of break down the groups

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:55.410
into personas of users and think
about the different interaction

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:57.430
models that people may be using.

00:00:57.430 --> 00:00:59.830
So we can break down into
a few different groups.

00:00:59.830 --> 00:01:02.430
For example, maybe thinking
about blind or low vision

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:05.430
users, deaf or hard of
hearing users, people

00:01:05.430 --> 00:01:08.310
with motor dexterity
challenges, and people

00:01:08.310 --> 00:01:10.920
who are considered
neurologically diverse,

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:14.070
or who have a range of
intellectual disabilities.

00:01:14.070 --> 00:01:16.740
But there's a huge
population of people

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:19.710
that absolutely needs to be
factored into this discussion.

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:22.020
And that's the aging
population, which

00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:24.810
has been growing and growing
since life expectancies have

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:27.096
thankfully been
increasing over the years.

00:01:27.096 --> 00:01:28.470
And the World
Health Organization

00:01:28.470 --> 00:01:32.430
estimates that by 2050
over 2 billion people

00:01:32.430 --> 00:01:34.970
will be over the age of 60.

00:01:34.970 --> 00:01:36.630
It's a huge population.

00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:40.290
And as we all age we may
experience disabilities

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:41.500
in different ways.

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:44.070
We may experience just
slight deterioration

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:48.180
of certain senses, of vision,
of hearing, of dexterity,

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:49.870
for example.

00:01:49.870 --> 00:01:51.640
Many other sorts of things.

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:54.240
So as technologists it's
really, really important

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:57.570
for us to factor in the needs
of this very important and very

00:01:57.570 --> 00:01:58.872
large population.

00:01:58.872 --> 00:02:00.330
So we're super
excited about today.

00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:01.980
Tim?

00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:04.560
TIM: Jeff Johnson is a
professor of computer science

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:06.530
at the University
of San Francisco.

00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:09.000
There he teaches courses
that introduce students

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.120
to computer science
and also special topics

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:14.400
in human-computer interaction.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:17.070
Beyond academia, Jeff has
worked as a UI designer

00:02:17.070 --> 00:02:21.360
and implementer, an engineering
manager, a usability tester,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.390
and a researcher at companies
like Cromemco, Xerox,

00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:28.770
US West, Hewlett-Packard
Labs, and Sun Microsystems.

00:02:28.770 --> 00:02:30.990
Building on a PhD
in psychology, Jeff

00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:33.960
has spent decades contributing
to our understanding

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:36.240
of human-computer interaction.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:38.310
He's addressed both
technical and social issues

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:41.370
including working as chair
of Computer Professionals

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:45.570
for Social Responsibility in
the late '80s and early '90s.

00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:48.720
In 2016, Professor
Johnson was recognized

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:51.180
with a Lifetime Achievement
in Practice Award

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:54.630
from SIGCHI, the ACM
special interest group

00:02:54.630 --> 00:02:57.300
on computer-human interaction.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:02:59.970
At the award ceremony, Stanford
professor Terry Winograd

00:02:59.970 --> 00:03:02.250
cited the influence of
Professor Johnson's books

00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:04.320
on interface design.

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:07.070
Many of these books
stem from the idea

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:08.820
that you learn more
from things that don't

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:11.570
work than from things that do.

00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:14.674
Today, Professor Johnson
will be sharing lessons

00:03:14.674 --> 00:03:16.590
that he's learned from
things that don't work.

00:03:16.590 --> 00:03:20.050
Because our bodies
change with age.

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:23.520
In designing user interfaces
for an aging population,

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:25.860
Jeff and his
collaborator Kate Finn

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:28.500
have built a
comprehensive resource

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:30.810
for technology
developers seeking

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:34.530
to produce products that can
be easily and successfully used

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:36.480
by older adults.

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:39.994
Please join me now in welcoming
Jeff and Kate to Google Today.

