00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:26.910
OK, so the population of the
world is aging on the average.

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:27.870
People live longer.

00:04:27.870 --> 00:04:29.490
Birth rates are low.

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:33.450
And so humanity on the
average is growing older.

00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:35.280
So let's look at some
numbers so that we

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:39.130
can see how much it's changing.

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:42.690
These are the top 10 countries
in the world that have

00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:45.900
populations of people over 50.

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:49.310
And by the way, in
our book we use 50

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:54.030
as the line for
indicating older adults.

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:55.920
The reason that we
picked that number

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:59.550
is that most of the research
that we read in preparation

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:02.490
of the book uses that number.

00:05:02.490 --> 00:05:04.950
So that age is an arbitrary age.

00:05:04.950 --> 00:05:07.170
Some researchers talk about 60.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:08.910
Some use 65.

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:10.710
But the bulk of them use 50.

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:14.660
And so we decided
to use that number.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.290
OK, so if we look at
these top 10 countries,

00:05:18.290 --> 00:05:23.450
China has nearly 400 million
people over the age of 50.

00:05:23.450 --> 00:05:28.820
India has about 230 million.

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:30.530
The US is third.

00:05:30.530 --> 00:05:34.150
Japan is fourth
and coming up fast.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:41.180
It's got the most rapidly
growing percentage

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:45.460
of people over 50.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:47.940
We can also look at the
information this way.

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.350
If you look at--

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:59.640
in 2015, basically
almost 20% of people

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:04.290
in the less developed areas
of the world were over 50.

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:06.690
Now, in the less
developed world, or what

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:10.020
we call the developing
world, population rates--

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:12.390
population growth
rates tend to be--

00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:14.190
birthrates tend to be higher.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:18.030
And therefore, there's a larger
percentage of younger adults.

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:22.230
And so the average
age of the population

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:27.276
tends to be lower than
in the developed world.

00:06:27.276 --> 00:06:28.650
So in the developed
world, we can

00:06:28.650 --> 00:06:32.280
see that in 2015
there was nearly 40%

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:35.670
of the population over 50.

00:06:35.670 --> 00:06:37.470
And then as you can
see, the numbers

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:41.235
are expected to grow over
the next several decades.

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:50.610
Yet another way to look
at what's going on is--

00:06:50.610 --> 00:06:55.260
people say, well, old
people don't use technology.

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:56.580
They don't go online.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:07:00.000
But that's not really true,
as we can see from this chart.

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:04.380
This is broken
out by age groups.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:12.240
And so as you can see, the
18- to 29-year-olds have

00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:19.800
pretty much been online and
are still that way nearly 100%.

00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:24.000
The next age group
is slightly less.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.710
And then when we get
to 50-year-olds to 64,

00:07:28.710 --> 00:07:31.050
it's slightly less.

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:32.400
But it's still growing.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:36.630
And then the fastest growing
demographic on online

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:41.220
is people over 65.

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:44.250
Now, this is a little bit--
this graph is a little bit

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:45.270
problematic.

00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:47.430
Because although
it sort of seems

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:54.300
to show these growth rates,
it's problematic because people

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:59.400
who are in one age group
age into another age group.

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:03.030
And therefore, of
course, this lower line

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:05.280
is going to go up as
the people who were

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:08.310
on this line become over 65.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:14.970
So this chart has been
shown by Pew Internet

00:08:14.970 --> 00:08:18.930
to show that people are
increasingly going online.

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:22.350
But I have some questions
about this chart.

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:27.810
So I prefer to look at it more
like this, where we take people

00:08:27.810 --> 00:08:31.080
by birth generation,
which you don't move out

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:32.669
of your birth generation.

00:08:32.669 --> 00:08:35.370
You stay in it.

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:38.010
So we have millennials, age--

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:44.310
people who were,
in 2016, 18 to 34.

00:08:44.310 --> 00:08:48.120
Then we have Gen-X,
younger boomers, et cetera.

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:50.340
And we can look at the
percentages of them

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:54.300
that have adopted
technology, what

00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.340
we call digital technology.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:09:00.540
Now, when we say technology
in this talk or when I say it,

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:02.910
I essentially mean
digital technology.

00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:06.490
Because of course, a horse
and a buggy is technology.

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:09.370
It's just older technology.

00:09:09.370 --> 00:09:15.030
So the question is
where are people--

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:16.840
what kind of technology
are people using?

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:18.720
So for the purpose
of the talk, I'm

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:20.940
referring to digital technology.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.910
We can also break
it up by device.

00:09:23.910 --> 00:09:30.690
So we can see that
for tablets, there's

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:33.840
not a lot of
variability in who's

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:37.110
using tablets by age group.

00:09:37.110 --> 00:09:40.110
There's some, but
not a whole lot.

00:09:40.110 --> 00:09:44.880
There's not that much with
cell phones of all types.

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:48.660
Nearly 100% of people 18 to 29--

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:50.460
or actually, it is--

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:54.240
Pew puts it at 100% are using--

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:56.940
and again, we're talking
about the developed world--

00:09:56.940 --> 00:10:01.500
are using digital
technology or cell phones.

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:03.940
And it doesn't vary
that much by age.

00:10:03.940 --> 00:10:07.890
The oldest age group,
65 and over, is at 80%.

00:10:07.890 --> 00:10:09.660
But when we look at
smartphones, there

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:14.340
is more of an age disparity.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:19.020
But again, those bars
are all going up.

00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:24.000
And especially the
smartphone for a 65-plus.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.160
That's going up.

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:28.410
Two years ago it was at 30%.

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:30.800
Now it's at 42.

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:33.980
OK, so it's going up.

00:10:37.700 --> 00:10:41.030
Laptops, and desktops,
and tablets, actually,

00:10:41.030 --> 00:10:44.030
have been seen to slip
in the general population

00:10:44.030 --> 00:10:48.590
over the last couple of years,
according to Pew Research.

00:10:48.590 --> 00:10:50.500
They've started to
drop a little bit.

00:10:54.930 --> 00:10:59.040
Now, the interesting thing about
the older than 50 population

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:01.380
is that technology,
digital technology,

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:06.760
can actually help
them quite a bit.

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:09.870
And here are some
quotes that were gleaned

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:14.670
from online sources of people
writing comments in response

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:18.460
to articles about
technology and older adults.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:23.650
And so here's an
example of a quote.

00:11:23.650 --> 00:11:25.740
"A Mac laptop opened
the world to me,

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:28.800
right here from
my kitchen table."

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:33.810
And it helped me because
of my physical disability.

00:11:33.810 --> 00:11:35.550
My mobility is limited.

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:40.530
So this one, for the
benefit of people

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:43.980
who may not be able to
see this very well says,

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:48.218
"I can keep in touch with
people all over the world."

00:11:48.218 --> 00:11:52.170
This one, "I feel so connected
in so much of the world.

00:11:52.170 --> 00:11:55.150
Art, music, nature,
comedy, humanity."

00:11:55.150 --> 00:11:59.070
And this one says, "Technology
has helped me move 19 times

00:11:59.070 --> 00:12:02.100
in the past nine years,
taking everything with me."

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:05.310
"I can't imagine going back
to life without a computer."

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:08.460
So these are the kinds
of things that technology

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:14.070
can do for people whose mobility
is a little bit limited,

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:17.970
or who are socially isolated.

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:24.070
On the other hand, if we don't
design the technology well,

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:28.330
then we'll also get comments
like these, which are also

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:31.750
gleaned from online sources.

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:33.100
"How can I make the font bigger?

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:33.970
I can't see it!"

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:37.300
I wish they'd stop changing
things for no good reason.

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:40.030
All the technology is
just so confusing to me.

00:12:40.030 --> 00:12:43.210
"Who thought thin grey
letters was a good idea?"

00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:44.800
I hear that one a lot.

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:46.750
"So much to remember!"

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:48.010
"What happened to the menus?"

00:12:48.010 --> 00:12:49.750
"I don't know
where to get help."

00:12:49.750 --> 00:12:52.720
"Is this the
website, or an app?"

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:55.690
Actually, that's-- I don't
think that's so age dependent.

00:12:55.690 --> 00:12:58.120
A lot of my students at USF
don't know the difference

00:12:58.120 --> 00:12:59.530
between a website and an app.

00:13:02.050 --> 00:13:04.220
"Where did my cursor go?"

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:07.100
Those kind of things.

00:13:07.100 --> 00:13:10.810
So poorly designed
technology can

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:15.980
lead to these kinds of problems
especially for older adults.

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:20.830
Now, these problems are not
restricted to older adults.

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:24.280
But they impact older adults.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:26.950
They tend to impact
older adults more

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:28.480
than the general population.

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:33.820
So illegible text,
bad passwords,

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:37.240
hard to remember
passwords, CAPTCHAs,

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:40.780
small targets, and the
difficulty of getting

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:41.350
tech support.

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:48.880
Those are all problems that
lots of people encounter.

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:52.070
But older adults
encounter them more often.

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:55.240
So let me just show you
an example of someone who

00:13:55.240 --> 00:14:01.360
is in a usability test
that Kate and I conducted

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:03.490
a few years ago.

00:14:03.490 --> 00:14:07.720
We were looking at older adults
using travel websites that

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:09.610
were aimed at older adults.

00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:13.720
So you may not know, but
there's a whole industry--

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:15.760
there's a whole segment
of the travel industry

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:19.540
that's aimed at people who
are essentially retired.

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:21.490
Because they have
money and time.

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:24.320
So there are various companies.

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:28.670
And so we tried a bunch of those
websites with older adults.

00:14:28.670 --> 00:14:30.620
Some of whom are
frequent travelers.

00:14:30.620 --> 00:14:36.350
So these are not people
who are homebound people.

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:38.710
And so you get quotes--
you get situations

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:40.277
like this in the test.

00:14:40.277 --> 00:14:41.650
